    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-11T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-11T21:00:00-05:00" n="119"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d119">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Kulangsu/132: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Amoy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVitty</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Amoy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-12T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 12, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>16. Yesterday morning Ang Hip Hoon of Amoy Peace Maintenance Committee killed in
                    International Settlement, Kulangsu. Last night Japanese landed 150 troops in
                    Settlement, placed guards at all jetties blockading the Settlement. Japanese
                    making numerous arrests in Settlement. This is the first incident occurring in
                    the Settlement and only occurred after Japanese had succeeded in forcing
                    Municipal Council to employ Japanese police.</p>
                <p>Transmitted to Embassy at Peiping, Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVitty</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
